    {
      "id": 79760,
      "name": "Robert UCL",
      "username": "Robert_UCL",
      "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/forums.trainerday.com/robert_ucl/{size}/1372_2.png",
      "created_at": "2025-06-25T19:55:15.006Z",
      "cooked": "<p>Getting excited for a climb doesn\u2019t hurt your performance. I\u2019d say that excitement can even work for you and give you a mental boost. Or a mental breakdown, depending on your fatigue and readiness. <img src=\"https://forums.trainerday.com/images/emoji/twitter/wink.png?v=12\" title=\":wink:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":wink:\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\"></p>\n<p>We always try to measure everything in our performance, so we can predict the end result.</p>\n<p>That is really boring, and one of the reasons why the UCI bans the glucose meters. If we could measure everything, there wouldn\u2019t be a race. We could simply compare stats and declare the winners without riding.</p>\n<p>The most beautiful part about cycling is the surprise of whether someone will crack or rise to the occasion.</p>",
